Defining REAL Data: Language

Did you know that more than 24 million people in the United States speak English less than very well?

 

When registering your patients, it will be important to ask about the language they prefer to use when they are communicating with health care providers. By asking, you will enable your organization’s health care providers to understand what language is best used to discuss the patient’s health care.

 

The Joint Commission provides you with a recommended way to ask patients about their language preference: Simply ask, “In what language do you prefer to discuss your health care?”  We will revisit this question later in this session.

 

When you ask questions as recommended by The Joint Commission, you will help your health care organization fulfill its requirements and avoid potential problems.

Defining REAL Data: Ethnicity

The concept of “ethnicity” may be confusing to some patients. For the purpose of collecting REAL data, just ask your patients if they are of Hispanic or Latino origin.

 

Some patients may give you a more detailed answer. We will explore how to help patients self-report later in this session.

Defining REAL Data: Race

For the purposes of helping your patients self-report their race, you will use these five broad categories:

 

•    American Indian or Alaska Native

•    Asian

•    Black or African American

•    Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander

•    White

 

You will learn more about the categories, including how to help your patients self-report later in this session.
